&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;sulphur&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Silver ornaments tarnish and turn black due to the formation of silver sulphide (Ag&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;S).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This reaction occurs when silver comes into contact with hydrogen sulphide (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;S) present in the air.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The chemical reaction is:&lt;strong&gt; 4Ag + 2H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;S + O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;rarr; 2Ag&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;S + 2H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hydrogen sulphide is often found in polluted air, emitted from sources like sewage, swamps, and industrial processes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Silver Tarnishing&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Tarnishing is a surface discoloration on silver, a result of the metal reacting with sulphur compounds in the air.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Tarnish is essentially corrosion that affects only the outer layers of the metal.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrogen Sulphide (H2S)&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a colorless gas with a characteristic odor of rotten eggs.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is produced naturally by the decomposition of organic matter and is also a by-product of industrial activities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Preventing Tarnish&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Storing silver in airtight containers can reduce exposure to air and pollutants.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Using anti-tarnish strips or bags can also help in preventing tarnish.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cleansing Tarnished Silver&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Tarnished silver can be cleaned using silver polish or homemade remedies like baking soda and vinegar.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A common method involves placing silver in aluminum foil and soaking it in a solution of baking soda and hot water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Endoplasmic reticulum&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-sourcepos=&quot;5:3-5:33&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Endoplasmic reticulum (ER):&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The endoplasmic reticulum is a network of membranous tubules and sacs found within the cytoplasm of eukaryotic cells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It functions as a passageway for the transport of materials within the cell, particularly proteins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are two main types of ER: rough ER (RER) and smooth ER (SER).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;RER is studded with ribosomes, making it a site for protein synthesis and modification.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;SER lacks ribosomes and is involved in lipid synthesis, detoxification, and calcium storage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The ER is a major part of the cells internal transport system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The ER plays a critical role in the folding of newly synthesized proteins.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-sourcepos=&quot;14:3-14:15&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plastids:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Plastids are membrane-bound organelles found in plant cells and some algae.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are involved in various functions, including photosynthesis (chloroplasts), storage of starch (amyloplasts), and pigment storage (chromoplasts).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Plastids do not function as a general intracellular transport system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are primarily focused on the production and storage of specific molecules.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Plastids have their own DNA.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Plastids are able to replicate independently of the cell.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-sourcepos=&quot;22:3-22:19&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mitochondria:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mitochondria are the &amp;quot;powerhouses&amp;quot; of the cell, responsible for cellular respiration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They generate ATP (adenosine triphosphate), the cell&amp;#39;s primary energy currency.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mitochondria have their own DNA and are involved in various cellular processes, but not in general intracellular transport as a main function.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mitochondria have a double membrane.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mitochondria are found in nearly all eukaryotic cells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The inner membrane of the mitochondria is folded into cristae, which increase the surface area for cellular respiration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-sourcepos=&quot;30:3-30:15&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ribosome:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ribosomes are cellular structures responsible for protein synthesis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can be found freely floating in the cytoplasm or attached to the rough endoplasmic reticulum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ribosomes read messenger RNA (mRNA) and assemble amino acids into polypeptide chains.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While they are crucial for protein production, they do not function as a general transport network.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ribosomes are made of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) and proteins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ribosomes are essential for all living cells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ribosomes are not membrane bound organelles.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;50 J&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The formula for kinetic energy (KE) is given by &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;K&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;E&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;=&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mfrac&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;1&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;2&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/mfrac&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;m&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;msup&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;v&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;2&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/msup&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-1-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-1&quot; style=&quot;width: 6.67em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 5.539em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.134em, 1005.54em, 2.801em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-2&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-3&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;K&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-4&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;E&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-5&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mfrac&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-6&quot; style=&quot;padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.479em; height: 0px; margin-right: 0.122em; margin-left: 0.122em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(3.336em, 1000.3em, 4.17em, -999.997em); top: -4.402em; left: 50%; margin-left: -0.176em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-7&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(3.336em, 1000.3em, 4.17em, -999.997em); top: -3.568em; left: 50%; margin-left: -0.176em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-8&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-9&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;m&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;msubsup&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-10&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.896em; height: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(3.396em, 1000.48em, 4.17em, -999.997em); top: -3.985em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-11&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;v&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; top: -4.342em; left: 0.479em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-12&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;K&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mfrac&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mfrac&gt;&lt;mi&gt;m&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-1&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; KE = \frac{1}{2}mv^2&lt;/script&gt;
	.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;m&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-2-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-13&quot; style=&quot;width: 1.074em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.896em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.61em, 1000.9em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-14&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-15&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;m&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;m&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-2&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; m&lt;/script&gt;
	is the mass of the body, and &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;v&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-3-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-16&quot; style=&quot;width: 0.598em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.479em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.61em, 1000.48em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-17&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-18&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;v&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-3&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; v&lt;/script&gt;
	is its velocity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Given the mass &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;m&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;=&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;1&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-4-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-19&quot; style=&quot;width: 3.336em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 2.741em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.372em, 1002.68em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-20&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-21&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;m&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-22&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-23&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;m&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-4&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; m = 1&lt;/script&gt;
	kg and velocity &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;v&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;=&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;10&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-5-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-24&quot; style=&quot;width: 3.455em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 2.86em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.372em, 1002.8em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-25&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-26&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;v&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-27&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-28&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;10&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;10&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-5&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; v = 10&lt;/script&gt;
	m/s.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Substituting the values into the formula: &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;K&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;E&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;=&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mfrac&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;1&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;2&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/mfrac&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;&amp;amp;#x00D7;&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;1&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;&amp;amp;#x00D7;&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo stretchy=&amp;quot;false&amp;quot;&amp;gt;(&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;10&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;msup&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo stretchy=&amp;quot;false&amp;quot;&amp;gt;)&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;2&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/msup&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-6-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-29&quot; style=&quot;width: 10.836em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 8.991em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.134em, 1008.99em, 2.801em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-30&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-31&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;K&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-32&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;E&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-33&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mfrac&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-34&quot; style=&quot;padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.479em; height: 0px; margin-right: 0.122em; margin-left: 0.122em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(3.336em, 1000.3em, 4.17em, -999.997em); top: -4.402em; left: 50%; margin-left: -0.176em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-35&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(3.336em, 1000.3em, 4.17em, -999.997em); top: -3.568em; left: 50%; margin-left: -0.176em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-36&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-37&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.241em;&quot;&gt;&amp;times;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-38&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.241em;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-39&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.241em;&quot;&gt;&amp;times;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-40&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.241em;&quot;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-41&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;10&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;msubsup&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-42&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.836em; height: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(3.039em, 1000.3em, 4.408em, -999.997em); top: -3.985em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-43&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; top: -4.342em; left: 0.42em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-44&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;K&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mfrac&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mfrac&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;times;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;times;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&quot;false&quot;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;10&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&quot;false&quot;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-6&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; KE = \frac{1}{2} \times 1 \times (10)^2&lt;/script&gt;
	.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This simplifies to &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;K&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;E&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;=&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;0.5&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;&amp;amp;#x00D7;&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;1&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;&amp;amp;#x00D7;&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;100&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-7-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-45&quot; style=&quot;width: 10.598em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 8.813em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.372em, 1008.75em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-46&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-47&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;K&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-48&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;E&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-49&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-50&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;0.5&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-51&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.241em;&quot;&gt;&amp;times;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-52&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.241em;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-53&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.241em;&quot;&gt;&amp;times;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-54&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.241em;&quot;&gt;100&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;K&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0.5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;times;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;times;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;100&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-7&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; KE = 0.5 \times 1 \times 100&lt;/script&gt;
	which equals &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mn&amp;gt;50&amp;lt;/mn&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-8-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-55&quot; style=&quot;width: 1.253em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.015em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.372em, 1000.96em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-56&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mn&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-57&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main;&quot;&gt;50&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;50&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-8&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; 50&lt;/script&gt;
	Joules.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Potential Energy&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Potential energy is the energy possessed by a body due to its position or state.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is calculated using the formula &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;P&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;E&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;=&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;m&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;g&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;h&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-9-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-58&quot; style=&quot;width: 5.836em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 4.824em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.313em, 1004.82em, 2.562em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-59&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-60&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;P&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-61&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;E&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-62&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-63&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;m&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-64&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;g&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-65&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;h&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;m&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
		&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-9&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; PE = mgh&lt;/script&gt;
		, where &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;m&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-10-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-66&quot; style=&quot;width: 1.074em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.896em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.61em, 1000.9em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-67&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-68&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;m&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;m&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
		&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-10&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; m&lt;/script&gt;
		is mass, &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;g&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-11-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-69&quot; style=&quot;width: 0.598em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.479em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.61em, 1000.48em, 2.562em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-70&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-71&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;g&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
		&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-11&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; g&lt;/script&gt;
		is acceleration due to gravity, and &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;h&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-12-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-72&quot; style=&quot;width: 0.717em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.598em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.313em, 1000.6em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-73&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-74&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;h&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
		&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-12&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; h&lt;/script&gt;
		is height.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mechanical Energy&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mechanical energy is the sum of kinetic and potential energy in a system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is conserved in an isolated system with no external forces.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Work-Energy Theorem&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This theorem states that the work done on an object is equal to the change in its kinetic energy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It can be represented as &lt;span class=&quot;MathJax&quot; data-mathml=&quot;&amp;lt;math xmlns=&amp;quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;W&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mo&amp;gt;=&amp;lt;/mo&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi mathvariant=&amp;quot;normal&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;amp;#x0394;&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;K&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;mi&amp;gt;E&amp;lt;/mi&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/math&amp;gt;&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Element-13-Frame&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot; style=&quot;position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;nobr aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-75&quot; style=&quot;width: 5.955em; display: inline-block;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 4.943em; height: 0px; font-size: 120%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: absolute; clip: rect(1.313em, 1004.94em, 2.384em, -999.997em); top: -2.199em; left: 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mrow&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-76&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-77&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;W&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mo&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-78&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-79&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.301em;&quot;&gt;&amp;Delta;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-80&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;K&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;mi&quot; id=&quot;MathJax-Span-81&quot; style=&quot;font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;&quot;&gt;E&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;MJX_Assistive_MathML&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;W&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&quot;normal&quot;&gt;&amp;Delta;&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;K&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
		&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-13&quot; type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt; W = \Delta KE&lt;/script&gt;
		.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Binary fission&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Binary fission&lt;/strong&gt; is a type of asexual reproduction common among prokaryotes such as bacteria.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In binary fission, an organism duplicates its genetic material and then divides into two equal-sized daughter cells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This process ensures that each daughter cell receives a copy of the parent organism&amp;#39;s genetic material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Binary fission is efficient and allows for rapid population growth, especially in favorable environments.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Regeneration&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Regeneration is the process by which certain organisms can regrow lost or damaged parts of their body.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include the regrowth of limbs in starfish or tails in lizards.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is different from binary fission as it involves repairing or replacing damaged structures rather than creating new organisms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Budding&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Budding is another form of asexual reproduction where a new organism develops from an outgrowth or bud due to cell division at one particular site.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is commonly observed in yeast and some invertebrates like hydra.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Unlike binary fission, budding results in the formation of a new organism while the parent organism remains.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Spore formation&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Spore formation is a method of asexual reproduction that involves the formation of spores by the parent organism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These spores are typically resistant to extreme conditions and can remain dormant for long periods.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When conditions become favorable, spores germinate to form new organisms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is a common reproductive strategy among fungi and some bacteria.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;unbalanced force&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An unbalanced force is necessary to change the state of motion of an object, as per Newton&amp;#39;s First Law of Motion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Applying an unbalanced force to an object on a horizontal table overcomes the frictional force between the object and the table surface.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the forces acting on an object are unbalanced, they cause a change in the object&amp;#39;s velocity, resulting in acceleration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The direction of the unbalanced force determines the direction in which the object will move.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An unbalanced force implies that the net force acting on the object is not zero, leading to motion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s First Law of Motion (Law of Inertia)&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;States that an object will remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by an external unbalanced force.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Highlights the concept of inertia, which is the tendency of objects to resist changes in their state of motion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Friction&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A force that opposes the relative motion or tendency of such motion of two surfaces in contact.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Can be reduced by applying lubricants or by using smoother surfaces.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Balanced Forces&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When two forces acting on an object are equal in size but opposite in direction, they are balanced forces.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Balanced forces do not cause a change in the motion of an object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Net Force&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The overall force acting on an object when all the individual forces acting on it are combined.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If the net force is not zero, the forces are unbalanced, leading to a change in the object&amp;#39;s motion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Faraday&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Michael Faraday discovered the principle of electromagnetic induction in 1831.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Faraday&amp;rsquo;s law of electromagnetic induction states that an electromotive force is induced in a conductor when there is a change in the magnetic field around it.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This discovery laid the foundation for the development of electric generators and transformers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Faraday&amp;#39;s experiments demonstrated that a changing magnetic field could produce an electric current, which is the basic principle behind many types of electrical devices.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electromagnetic Induction:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the production of voltage across a conductor situated in a changing magnetic field or a conductor moving through a stationary magnetic field.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Faraday&amp;rsquo;s law mathematically describes how a time varying magnetic field creates an electric field.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Electromagnetic induction is the working principle behind electrical components like inductors and transformers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lenz&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Formulated by Heinrich Lenz in 1834, it states that the direction of the induced current will be such that it opposes the change in the magnetic field that produced it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Lenz&amp;#39;s Law is a consequence of the law of conservation of energy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Electromagnetic Induction:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in the generation of electric power in power plants.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Essential in the functioning of transformers, which transfer electric energy between circuits.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Induction motors utilize this principle to convert electrical energy into mechanical energy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ductility&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ductility&lt;/strong&gt; is the property of a material that allows it to be drawn into thin wires.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This property is most commonly observed in metals such as gold, silver, copper, and aluminum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gold&lt;/strong&gt; is known to be one of the most ductile metals, capable of being drawn into very fine wires.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The measure of ductility is typically expressed as a percentage of elongation or the reduction of area in a tensile test.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ductility is essential for manufacturing processes like wire drawing and tube making.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Malleability&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Malleability is the ability of a material to be hammered or rolled into thin sheets without breaking.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Like ductility, malleability is a property of metals, allowing them to be shaped and formed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gold and silver are also highly malleable, making them useful for various industrial and jewelry applications.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tensile Strength&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Tensile strength is the maximum amount of tensile stress that a material can withstand before failure.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is an important property for materials that are used in structures and machines.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;High tensile strength materials are often also ductile, but this is not always the case.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Brittleness&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Brittleness is the tendency of a material to break or shatter without significant deformation when under stress.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Brittle materials, like glass, ceramics, and some polymers, have low ductility and malleability.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These materials are often used where high hardness and low deformability are required.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plasticity&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Plasticity is the ability of a material to undergo permanent deformation without breaking.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This property is crucial for processes such as forging, molding, and stamping.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Metals and polymers typically exhibit high plasticity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Milk of magnesia&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-sourcepos=&quot;5:3-5:23&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Milk of magnesia:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Milk of magnesia is a colloidal dispersion of magnesium hydroxide in water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a sol, which is a type of colloid where solid particles are dispersed in a liquid medium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The magnesium hydroxide particles are very small and remain suspended in the water, giving it a milky appearance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is commonly used as an antacid and laxative.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The particles in milk of magnesia do not settle easily due to their small size and the presence of stabilizing agents.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The particle size of the suspended Mg(OH)2 is within the colloidal range.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-sourcepos=&quot;13:3-13:17&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Face cream:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Face cream is an emulsion, which is a mixture of two or more immiscible liquids (typically oil and water).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Emulsions are different from sols, as they involve the dispersion of liquids in liquids.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Face creams contain emulsifiers that stabilize the mixture and prevent the liquids from separating.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are designed to provide moisture and other beneficial ingredients to the skin.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Face cream is a complex mixture of many different substances.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The consistency of face cream is due to the emulsifiers present.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-sourcepos=&quot;21:3-21:11&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Foam:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Foam is a colloidal dispersion where gas bubbles are trapped within a liquid or solid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a type of dispersion known as a foam, not a sol.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of foams include whipped cream and shaving cream.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Foams are characterized by their light and airy texture.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The stability of a foam is dependent on the surface tension of the liquid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Foams can be either liquid or solid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-sourcepos=&quot;29:3-29:13&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rubber:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rubber, in its raw form, can be a latex, which is a colloidal dispersion, but processed rubber is a solid polymer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Processed rubber is not a sol.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Raw latex is a colloidal dispersion of polymer particles in a water based liquid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Vulcanized rubber is a solid material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rubber is an elastic polymer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The properties of rubber are due to its long chain polymer structure.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kulhad non-biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt; materials are those that can be broken down by &lt;strong&gt;natural processes&lt;/strong&gt; and decomposed by microorganisms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kulhad&lt;/strong&gt; is a traditional Indian cup made from &lt;strong&gt;clay&lt;/strong&gt;, which is an &lt;strong&gt;eco-friendly&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt; material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since &lt;strong&gt;Kulhad&lt;/strong&gt; is made from &lt;strong&gt;natural clay&lt;/strong&gt;, it easily decomposes back into the soil, contributing to environmental sustainability.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using &lt;strong&gt;Kulhad&lt;/strong&gt; helps reduce the use of &lt;strong&gt;plastic&lt;/strong&gt; and other &lt;strong&gt;non-biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt; materials, thereby reducing environmental pollution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In contrast, materials like &lt;strong&gt;plastic&lt;/strong&gt; take hundreds of years to decompose and can cause significant environmental damage.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Paper cup - biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Paper cups&lt;/strong&gt; are typically made from &lt;strong&gt;wood pulp&lt;/strong&gt; and are &lt;strong&gt;biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They can decompose naturally and are often &lt;strong&gt;recyclable&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plastic glass - non-biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plastic glasses&lt;/strong&gt; are made from &lt;strong&gt;synthetic polymers&lt;/strong&gt;, which are &lt;strong&gt;non-biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They can persist in the environment for hundreds of years, causing pollution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vegetable - biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vegetables&lt;/strong&gt; are organic and &lt;strong&gt;biodegradable&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They decompose naturally through the action of &lt;strong&gt;microorganisms&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alkyne, alkene, and alkane hydrocarbons, respectively&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C2H2&lt;/strong&gt; is known as acetylene and is classified as an &lt;strong&gt;alkyne hydrocarbon&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C2H4&lt;/strong&gt; is known as ethylene and is classified as an &lt;strong&gt;alkene hydrocarbon&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C2H6&lt;/strong&gt; is known as ethane and is classified as an &lt;strong&gt;alkane hydrocarbon&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Alkynes have a triple bond between carbon atoms, alkenes have a double bond, and alkanes have single bonds only.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These classifications are based on the type of carbon-carbon bonds present in the molecule.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrocarbon Types:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alkanes:&lt;/strong&gt; Saturated hydrocarbons with only single bonds between carbon atoms (e.g., methane, ethane).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alkenes:&lt;/strong&gt; Unsaturated hydrocarbons with at least one double bond between carbon atoms (e.g., ethylene, propylene).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alkynes:&lt;/strong&gt; Unsaturated hydrocarbons with at least one triple bond between carbon atoms (e.g., acetylene, propyne).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bond Characteristics:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Single bonds (sigma bonds) allow for free rotation around the bond axis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Double bonds (one sigma and one pi bond) restrict rotation and create a planar structure.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Triple bonds (one sigma and two pi bonds) are linear and the shortest and strongest among the three types.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Uses of Hydrocarbons:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Alkanes are primarily used as fuels and lubricants.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Alkenes are used in the production of polymers and as intermediates in chemical reactions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Alkynes are used in welding and as precursors to other chemicals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Isomerism:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hydrocarbons can exhibit structural isomerism, where compounds have the same molecular formula but different structures.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Geometric isomerism is seen in alkenes due to the restricted rotation around the double bond.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
